-- SHADOW-SEMANTICS cell D21 (matrix row 29): the S5 CARVE-OUT at MULTI-TYPARAM
-- width.  `useIface : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int` calls `get` on its own dict-bound
-- `=>` constraint variable, inside a module that shadows `get`.  S5's carve-out
-- says such a receiver DISPATCHES -- writing `Ix a i =>` is an explicit, written-
-- down request to resolve through the interface.
--
-- ⚠️ IT DOES NOT, at multi-typaram width -- AND THE CAUSE IS IN THE PARSER, NOT IN
-- THE SHADOW MACHINERY.  See issue #604.  `Ty`'s `TyApp Ty Ty` (frontend/ast.mdk:31)
-- is BINARY, so `Ix a i` parses as `TyApp (TyApp (TyCon "Ix") (TyVar "a")) (TyVar "i")`.
-- `extractConstraints` (frontend/parser.mdk:1678-1682) matches only the ONE-argument
-- shape `TyApp (TyCon iface _) arg`, so the outer `TyApp` -- whose first field is
-- itself a `TyApp` -- falls through to `_ = []`.  EVERY >=2-ARGUMENT CONSTRAINT IS
-- SILENTLY DISCARDED, yielding `TyConstrained []`.
--
-- So S5's antecedent ("a dict-bound `=>` constraint variable") is FALSE by the time
-- typecheck runs: there is no constraint left to be bound by.  `definerReceiverIsDictVar`
-- handles a multi-argument constraint correctly -- IT NEVER RECEIVES ONE.  The
-- occurrence falls to S2 and `useIface` monomorphises to the standalone's domain
-- (`Int -> Int -> Int`), making the `Box` call a located reject.  An S5 GAP, NOT an S7
-- violation: check/run/build agree exactly, and are conformant TO THE PROGRAM THEY WERE
-- GIVEN -- which is not the one written below.
-- Expected: check/run/build all REJECT (`Int vs Box`) at the `useIface (Box 3) 1` call.
--
-- ⭐ WHY THIS CELL EXISTS.  It is the receiver-PROVENANCE axis (grounded / literal /
-- DICT-BOUND) crossed with the typaram-arity axis -- the crossing d11 alone could not
-- reach, and the corpus was blind to it.  On `eedd1482` (pre-#54) this exact file was
-- **SILENT WRONGNESS of the P0-20 kind**, strictly worse than d11's loud panic:
--
--   check  -> exit 0, and reported `useIface : a -> b -> Int` -- the `Ix a i =>`
--             constraint SILENTLY DROPPED from the scheme it printed
--   run    -> E-PANIC `unknown op '*'`
--   build  -> exit 0, and the shipped binary printed `69867028434928` then `3`,
--             at exit 0: a RAW HEAP POINTER rendered as an Int
--
-- #54 closed that by bringing multi-typaram interfaces into the definer machinery;
-- the reject below is the S2 default it now (correctly, consistently) lands on.  The
-- residual is only that S5's carve-out cannot re-open it, and that residual is #604's
-- to close, not this machinery's.  A cell that trades a garbage-pointer miscompile for
-- a located reject is a fix; this row pins the trade so the remaining half cannot rot,
-- and goes RED the day #604 lands -- ⚠️ which is the signal to RE-PROBE this cell, NOT
-- to assume it becomes 3 then 6.  Both of `check`'s pre-#54 symptoms above are #604:
-- the dropped constraint in the scheme, and the `() =>` the formatter wrote (an EMPTY
-- constraint LIST printed -- `TyConstrained []` -- not a missing constraint).  They
-- were filed as two unrelated bugs; they are one.
-- 🚨 DO NOT RUN `medaka fmt --write` ON THIS FILE.  It DESTROYS the `Ix a i =>`
-- constraint below, rewriting it to `() =>`, which is not even parseable
-- (`expected type atom`).  That is NOT a formatter bug: the parser handed fmt a
-- `TyConstrained []` (see above), and `() =>` is what an EMPTY constraint list prints
-- as -- the formatter is faithfully rendering the tree it was given.  Same root cause,
-- issue #604.  The pre-commit hook excludes `test/` from `fmt --check`, which is the
-- only reason this file can be committed at all.
interface Ix a i where
  get : a -> i -> Int

data Box = Box Int

impl Ix Box Int where
  get (Box n) i = n + i

get : Int -> Int -> Int
get n i = n * i

useIface : Ix a i => a -> i -> Int
useIface x i = get x i

main =
  println (useIface (Box 3) 1)
  println (get 3 1)
